README.md
     9→# Nano-vLLM
    11→A lightweight vLLM implementation built from scratch.
    12→
    13→## Key Features
    15→* 🚀 **Fast offline inference** - Comparable inference speeds to vLLM
    16→* 📖 **Readable codebase** - Clean implementation in ~ 1,200 lines of Python code
    17→* ⚡ **Optimization Suite** - Prefix caching, Tensor Parallelism, Torch compilation, CUDA graph, etc.
    18→
    19→## Installation
    21→```bash
    22→pip install git+https://github.com/GeeeekExplorer/nano-vllm.git
    23→```
    24→
    25→## Model Download
    27→To download the model weights manually, use the following command:
    28→```bash
    29→huggingface-cli download --resume-download Qwen/Qwen3-0.6B \
    30→  --local-dir ~/huggingface/Qwen3-0.6B/ \
    31→  --local-dir-use-symlinks False
    32→```
    33→
    34→## Quick Start
    36→See `example.py` for usage. The API mirrors vLLM's interface with minor differences in the `LLM.generate` method:
    37→```python
    38→from nanovllm import LLM, SamplingParams
    39→llm = LLM("/YOUR/MODEL/PATH", enforce_eager=True, tensor_parallel_size=1)
    40→sampling_params = SamplingParams(temperature=0.6, max_tokens=256)
    41→prompts = ["Hello, Nano-vLLM."]
    42→outputs = llm.generate(prompts, sampling_params)
    43→outputs[0]["text"]
    44→```
    45→
    46→## Benchmark
    48→See `bench.py` for benchmark.
    49→
    50→**Test Configuration:**
    51→- Hardware: RTX 4070 Laptop (8GB)
    52→- Model: Qwen3-0.6B
    53→- Total Requests: 256 sequences
    54→- Input Length: Randomly sampled between 100–1024 tokens
    55→- Output Length: Randomly sampled between 100–1024 tokens
    56→
    57→**Performance Results:**
    58→| Inference Engine | Output Tokens | Time (s) | Throughput (tokens/s) |
    59→|----------------|-------------|----------|-----------------------|
    60→| vLLM           | 133,966     | 98.37    | 1361.84               |
    61→| Nano-vLLM      | 133,966     | 93.41    | 1434.13               |
    62→
    63→
